%%%
FAQ-HSP-Q01
%%
Configuration Problems
%%

Since Mini Vend can run on a number of platforms, basically any UNIX
with Perl 5, there are a lot of "gotchas" in the portability end.
If you have a problem, you should check the MiniVend web site for
information about patches and problems already solved.


%%%
FAQ-HSP-Q02
%%
VLINK compile problems
%%
The latest version of vlink.c, svend.c, and mat.c have been compiled on
(at least) the following systems without problem:


<XMP>
        BSD2.0 (Pentium/x86)
        SunOS 4.1.4
        Solaris 2.4
        IRIX 5.3
        Linux 1.2.13
        Digital UNIX (OSF/Alpha)

</XMP>

Make sure that you have run the configure program in the src directory.
If you used MiniVend's configuration, and selected the default
of compiling those programs, the configuration was run, and
all of the proper libraries should be used.

Known problems:


<DL>
<DT>IRIX</DT>
<DD>vlink.c shipped with MiniVend 1.02 ailed with the setenv call
    not found during the link
    phase.  The solution is to edit vlink.c to use the putenv() call
    instead (as is used for SunOS).  If you don't feel comfortable
    with that, you can download the latest vlink.c from the URL:
</DD>
<DT>SOLARIS using GCC</DT>
<DD>The socket libraries sometimes are not picked
	up, and compiling with -lsocket seems to solve it.  Also, at least
	one site had problems with setregid() and setreuid() calls -- that
	does not occur on all sites. Many pre-compiled GCCs are not properly
	set up for your system -- the solution is usually to use the
	precompiled GCC to compile the latest version of GCC on your 
	system. If you can't do that, try compiling with -DSVR4. In the
	GCC of at least one site I saw, this was not the default define.
	<P>
	MiniVend 1.03 should handle this one.
</DD>
</DL>
See the <A HREF="http://www.iac.net/~mikeh/bugs.html">bug list</A>
for possible patches.
%%%
FAQ-HSP-Q03
%%
No DBM implementation
%%
This shows up when trying to start the MiniVend server, with a message:


<XMP>
        No DBM defined! MiniVend can't run.

</XMP>

This could be one of two things. MiniVend 1.02 has
a problem with automatic DBM detection on Perl versions lower than
5.002 -- you can get a patch (from the <A HREF="http://www.iac.net/~mikeh/bugs.html"> bug list</A>).

Or you might not have a proper DBM for use with MiniVend.  MiniVend relies
on DBM databases for a number of things, most notably the session database.
Some operating systems (or Perl incantations) don't support one of the
three DBMs MiniVend will recognize (GDBM, DB_File, and NDBM).

Perl always has SDBM available.  However, MiniVend can create some
large session records, larger than the 1024 byte total key/value
limitation of SDBM. This will very probably cause problems. (Some old
versions of NDBM will also have this limit.)

If you want to try to use 1024-byte NDBM or SDBM, perhaps just for testing
purposes, you can.  SDBM will take a small edit of minivend.pl:


<XMP>
        perl -npi -e 's/NDBM/SDBM/g' minivend.pl

</XMP>

If you have MiniVend 1.02, you will also have to obtain the patch from
the MiniVend web site for enabling NDBM.

The better solution is to obtain the DB_File library module from a CPAN
site and install it in the VendRoot/Vend directory.
%%%
FAQ-HSP-Q04
%%
Error -- the MiniVend server was not running...
%%
This indicates that VLINK is not communicating with the MiniVend server.
The server must be running, first of all.  If you didn't start it,
you can do so by going to the <EM>MiniVend home directory</EM> and typing:


<XMP>
        bin/start

</XMP>

You can check to see if your server is running by typing:


<XMP>
    Linux, SunOS, BSD:    ps -ax | grep minivend
    Most other systems:   ps -elf | grep minivend

</XMP>

If VLINK is not communicating with the server, there are a number of possible
reasons.  First, if you are trying to run MiniVend on an ISP, go to the section
about ISP problems -- it is probably one of those.  If you are running
MiniVend on a single machine, it is probably one of:

        1. Permissions problems
        2. MiniVend on NFS-mounted file system

Permissions are easy.  If you for some reason can't run VLINK as an SUID
program (SUID to your user ID, not to root), then you will need to 
make permissions more permissive.  See the MiniVend documentation
for how to use the ReadPermission and WritePermission directives to
make the session files and sockets 'group' or 'world' readable and writable.
If you can make your UID, or the one you have chosen to own MiniVend, the
same group as your HTTP user, then you can make the files group read-write.
If you can't, you will have to set the dreaded 'world' permissions.

If you are running MiniVend on an NFS-mounted file system it cannot run
in server mode, because UNIX-domain sockets don't work on NFS. You will
need to change to static mode from server mode, or better yet, put
MiniVend on a filesystem that is directly mounted.

%%%
FAQ-ISP-Q01
%%
No shell access allowed on my ISP.
%%
If this is the case, you are almost certainly out of luck. While
it would be possible for the ISP to configure MiniVend for you,
most don't have the time or patience to deal with it unless you
are paying them a lot of money.

You could contact Mike Heins for some pointers to ISPs who have
MiniVend compatibility, or wait for a future release (which may
have a Perl client program). Or if you had access to an identical
system with which to configure MiniVend and compile VLINK, you might
have some success.

%%%
FAQ-ISP-Q02
%%
No C compiler to compile VLINK or SVEND.
%%
As of this writing, with MiniVend 1.02 being the latest version,
this is a show stopper.  Since VLINK and SVEND need certain values
set in the source before compilation, a pre-compiled version will
not work.  If your ISP will compile programs for you, or you can
get access to a system with the same operating system and libraries,
you might have luck.  But probably you won't.

%%%
FAQ-ISP-Q03
%%
Perl version too low
%%
MiniVend requires Perl 5.001m or higher, and suggests 5.002. Earlier
patchlevels of perl 5 may work, but no problems with them will be touched by
the author.

Perl 4 will definitely not work -- and there isn't even a remote
chance it will in the future.

%%%
FAQ-ISP-Q04
%%
No usable DBM implementation
%%
If your provider compiled Perl such that it doesn't have a GDBM,
DB_File, or NDBM database defined, you will have problems.  MiniVend
can create some large session records, larger than the 1024 byte
total key/value limitation of SDBM (which is always there). This will
very probably cause problems. (Some old versions of NDBM will
also have this limit.)

If you want to try to use 1024-byte NDBM or SDBM, perhaps just for testing
purposes, you can.  SDBM will take a small edit of minivend.pl:

        perl -npi -e 's/NDBM/SDBM/g'

You will also have to obtain the patch from the MiniVend web site
for enabling older DBM versions.

The better solution is to obtain the DB_File library module from a CPAN
site and install it in the VendRoot/Vend directory.


%%%
FAQ-ISP-Q05
%%
MiniVend runs, but it's sooo sllooowww...
%%
If you are forced to run MiniVend in static mode because of ISP problems
(see below), you may find that the pages take 10-30 seconds to load
and display.  This is almost certainly due to an ISP system that has
inadequate memory or network bandwidth.  On a moderately fast ISP
server with sufficient memory, pages should display in from 1-5 seconds.

%%%
FAQ-ISP-Q06
%%
Error - The MiniVend server was not running...
%%
The below all assume you were able to start the MiniVend server.

This could be almost anything, but with a properly configured MiniVend
it is almost undoubtedly due to your CGI-BIN and/or your MiniVend
directory being located on a different filesystem than the actual machine
that is executing the program.  VLINK uses UNIX-domain sockets, which
don't work on NFS-mounted filesystems.

A TCP version of VLINK called TLINK is distributed with MiniVend,
along with a Server.pm.tcp module. This will take some prodigious
hacking to make work -- be forewarned. MiniVend 1.03 may contain
a Perl-based TCP client, which will make this easier.  But one
caveat -- using the TCP client will make transactions TOTALLY 
INSECURE.  This is one reason MiniVend uses UNIX-domain sockets,
which are always on the same filesystem as the program, meaning
no unencrypted SSL data gets sent over the wire.

%%%
FAQ-ISP-Q07
%%
DOCUMENT CONTAINS NO DATA error on SVEND
%%
See the question "The MiniVend server was not running". 
This probably means that SVEND is unable to find the
minivend.pl program and run it.  Unlike VLINK, SVEND will work on
NFS-mounted file systems, but it must have the proper path (and the
proper paths/URLs must be configured into MiniVend) for it to work.
Without a competent and understanding support person from your ISP, this
will be difficult to resolve.

%%%
FAQ-ISP-Q08
%%
My provider runs Windows NT
%%
You have no option -- MiniVend is unlikely to ever work on Windows NT.
There are a number of commercial programs available, and you might
someday find a freeware one.  But not MiniVend.
%%%
FAQ-ISP-Q09
%%
It still will not work.
%%
There is another wild-card. If your ISP doesn't use CGI-WRAP or another
program that runs your CGIs as your UID, and the VLINK or SVEND program
is not SUID, you will need to make your files world-readable and
writable (ugghh!) to make it work.  Set the ReadPermission and
WritePermission directives to 'world'.  (Also see the MiniVend web site
for a <A HREF="http://www.iac.net/~mikeh/bugs.html">patch</A> to the Server.pm in MiniVend 1.02).

%%%
FAQ-ISP-Q10
%%
MiniVend server only runs for a while, then dies.
%%
Many ISPs don't allow your user ID to run a program unless it is logged
in!  The moment a watchdog program notices a daemon running with a
non-logged-in UID, it terminates the program.  Or it terminates programs
that haven't been active for XX minutes.  Contact your ISP about this --
they may be able to do something for you.  
%%%
FAQ-SET-Q01
%%
Can I run multiple catalogs on one server?
%%
Yes, if you run multiple instances of the MiniVend server. The only
way is to install two complete MiniVend distributions, code and
all. Then all you need to do is rename the vlink executable to another
name and install it in the cgi-bin/ directory.

With disk space as cheap as it is, it didn't seem that saving the
200K or so of disk space was necessary. Memory is another consideration,
however, and if requests keep coming in, a feature to run multiple
catalogs from one server will probably be added.  Keep posted.

